100.description: Let your users be the voice talent with Actions on Google. Learn how to design, develop, and distribute rich conversational experiences with Node.js. We‚Äôll show you how to approach voice-driven, natural language interactions with Dialogflow‚Äôs powerful bot platform.
100.title: Get talking with Actions on Google

101.description: In this talk, I will provide a short overview of bootstrapping a low cost application leveraging GCP's "Platform as a Service" offerings. The focus of the talk will be how to easily leverage many of machine analysis services provided by Google such as Image Analysis, Video Analysis, Speech Analysis and Text Analysis. Time permitting, I'd also like to discuss how GCP's services can help scale from 1 user to 1 million users.
101.title: Visual Analysis with Google Could Platform

102.description: Immersive virtual reality (VR), augmented reality (AR), and mixed reality (MR) are becoming mainstream while their software and hardware are rapidly changing.  They introduce new and novel usability issues ranging from high-level project methodology down to detailed design of sensory elements in their user interfaces. They also sometimes affect non-users who are interacting with AR and MR users.   Key questions include defining (a) new usability-design strategies and (b) new procedures and processes for usability testing.  The Five-Finger project life cycle and the GAINS‚Ñ¢ design framework provide an approach to answering these questions and designing excellent user interfaces.
102.title: How to Save Time and Decrease Risk in VR/AR/MR User-Interface Design

103.description: Most applications have some sort of authentication system. Authentication is a hard problem for any developer. It needs to be safe, secure and easy for the user. In this talk, we will explore the tools provided by the Google Identity platform to help you build frictionless and secure authentication for your application.
103.title: Simplifying Signups with the Google Identity Platform

104.description: Android TV‚Äôs home screen has received a makeover with Android Oreo. With this update, users can decide what to watch from multiple apps at once from the home screen. In addition, the Google Assistant is also available for users to discover and control playback of content on their Android TV. We will look at how to surface your app‚Äôs content on the home screen by creating channels. We will also examine how to integrate your app with the Google Assistant with MediaSession.
104.title: Android TV's new home screen

105.description: Kotlin has a lot of great features that improve developer productivity and make the overall code base more stable. This all works great when you're entire code base is written in Kotlin. However, while Kotlin adoption is growing by leaps and bounds, the fact is that many applications and libraries are still on Java and will be for some time. This means, if you're a library provider like Realm that 100k+ developers rely on, you must provide an API that works well for both platforms. In this talk, you'll learn about some of the challenges faced and approaches taken by Realm to solve this problem and how you might apply these same approaches to your own libraries. You'll also learn about some of the key Kotlin features they used to simplify Realm Mobile Database development with Kotlin.
105.title: Building Libraries for Kotlin

106.description: Lombok, Retrofit, Dagger. These project all have one thing in common; they all use Java's annotation API.  Many developers look at these libraries as black magic which is effective but inscrutable.  No more!  In this session developers will learn how they can create their own annotation library in order to reduce boilerplate code and improve the lives of their fellow developers.  We'll shed light on how to create annotations, how to parse the AST using the AbstractProcessor, and how to generate code using the JavaPoet library. By the end of this session developers will come away with a better understanding of how annotations work and how they can create them themselves.
106.title: Annotation Processing - Demystifying Java's Dark Arts

107.description: This talk will provide a broad overview of some of the most popular machine learning algorithms and techniques. Specific topics may include Decision Trees, Random Forests, Neural Networks, and associated ensemble methods (gradient boosting vs. bagging/bootstrapping). Attendees can expect  a high-level overview of techniques, a review of the circumstances under which they are and aren't appropriate for use, and a brief crash course on how to implement some popular algorithms using open source software.
107.title: Using Popular Machine Learning Models and Techniques

108.description: The Flutter SDK looks incredibly promising. Let's face it though, not a lot of us are Dart developers. Let's see some of the basics of Dart & Flutter to implement both iOS & Android apps using Firebase as a backend. In this talk, we'll first take a look at Dart, see its similarities & differences compared to Java. Then take a look at what it takes to write an app with one codebase for Android & iOS. Finally we'll pull our conference data into our app using Firebase as our datasource.
108.title: Developing iOS and Android apps with Flutter

109.description: Currently, we are in the wave of IoT data collection. We are figuring out ways to attach microchips and sensors to everything to collect as much data possible -- this is solely for one purpose: Machine Learning. The next big part of IoT is learning from all the information we can collect. This talk will cover the process of collecting data from hardware and using TensorFlow to predict future values. With this foundation, one can use these same learnings to build more complex ML & IoT solutions.
109.title: Predicting the Internet of Things With Tensorflow

110.description: Take your build toolchain to the next level by putting all your build tools (gulp, maven, gradle, grunt, make, rake) into a Docker container. In this talk we'll go over the basics of getting started putting your toolchain into Docker, explore a few examples, and talk about common problems you might encounter.
110.title: Dockerize Your Build Toolchain

111.description: Google Home is a voice-activated speaker powered by the Google Assistant. While the Assistant is good at answering general questions, you can make Google Home even smarter by building your own app for it and publishing that app to the world. In this session we will go through the steps to do just that, including how to tune the AI, starting from a blank slate.
111.title: Build your own app for Google Home

112.description: At first glance, visualizing data in JavaScript seems too daunting to approach. Fortunately there are open source JavaScript libraries which help developers create compelling visualizations. We will talk about D3.js, DC.js and CrossFilter.js.
112.title: Feed your inner data scientist: JavaScript tools for data visualization and filtering.

114.description: This talk will provide a broad overview of some of the most popular machine learning algorithms and techniques. Specific topics may include Decision Trees, Random Forests, Neural Networks, and associated ensemble methods (gradient boosting vs. bagging/bootstrapping). Attendees can expect a high-level overview of techniques, a review of the circumstances under which they are and aren't appropriate for use, and a brief crash course on how to implement some popular algorithms using open source software.
114.title: Genomic Data Science and Personalized Medicine

115.description: Getting new features (and bug fixes) into the hands of your users is an important part of the app lifecycle. Scripting and automation can help you get the most of your submission process by ensuring efficiency and stability when shipping new versions of your app. This talk will cover several tips and tricks to trim your submission/release process down to a reliable and reproducible set of commands.
115.title: Ship It Faster: Making the Most of Mobile App Submission
